
@startuml

' Define classes
class Game {
  - board: Board
  - players: List<Player>
  - currentTurn: int
  - actionDeck: Deck<ActionCard>
  - hiddenTile: Tile
}

class Board {
  - tiles: List<Tile>
  - connectionPieces: List<ConnectionPiece>
}

class Tile {
  - position: Position
  - isHidden: boolean
  - isActionTile: boolean
  - actionDuration: int
  - color: Color
}

class ConnectionPiece {
  - fromTile: Tile
  - toTile: Tile
  - isUsed: boolean
}

class Player {
  - color: Color
  - position: Position
  - hasTurn: boolean
}

class ActionCard {
  - type: ActionType
  - effect: String
}

enum ActionType {
  EXTRA_TURN,
  CONNECT_TILES,
  REMOVE_CONNECTION,
  MOVE_TO_TILE,
  LOSE_TURN
}

class Position {
  - x: int
  - y: int
}

class Color {
  - name: String
}

' Associations
Game --> Board
Game --> Player : has
Game --> ActionCard : uses
Game --> Tile : has
Game --> ConnectionPiece : has

Player --> Tile : is on
Player --> ActionCard : receives

Board --> Tile : contains
Board --> ConnectionPiece : contains

Tile --> ConnectionPiece : connected to

@enduml

### Explanation of the Diagram:
- **Game**: The central class representing the game state. It holds the board, players, action deck, and hidden tile.
- **Board**: Contains the layout of tiles and connection pieces.
- **Tile**: Represents a single tile on the board with properties like position, color, and whether it's an action tile or hidden.
- **ConnectionPiece**: Links two adjacent tiles.
- **Player**: Each player has a color and a position on the board.
- **ActionCard**: Defines different types of actions that can be triggered when landing on an action tile.
- **Position**: A simple class to represent coordinates on the board.
- **Color**: Enumerates the colors of the players’ pieces.

This diagram captures the core structure and relationships of the *Tile-O* system as described in the requirements.